  "response": "Yes, it is possible to boot Windows from an SD card, but there are some important considerations:\n\n1. Prerequisites:\n- Your computer must support booting from SD card\n- You'll need a bootable Windows installation media on the SD card\n- The SD card should be at least 8GB (16GB recommended)\n\n2. Methods to create bootable SD card:\n- Use Windows USB/DVD Download Tool\n- Rufus software\n- Windows Media Creation Tool\n\n3. Steps:\n- Download Windows ISO\n- Use one of the above tools to create bootable media\n- Insert SD card\n- Change boot order in BIOS/UEFI to boot from SD card\n\n4. Recommendations:\n- Use a high-speed, Class 10 or UHS-1 SD card\n- Format SD card before creating bootable media\n- Be prepared for slower performance compared to HDD/SSD\n\n5. Limitations:\n- Performance will be slower\n- SD cards have limited write cycles\n- Not a long-term solution\n\nAlternative options:\n- Use an external USB hard drive\n- Recover data from crashed hard drive\n- Get a replacement hard drive\n\nConsult a professional if you're unsure about the process.",
